Using Spatial Data

Part 1: Plotting Elevation differences

In this first part of the exercise, we consider elevation data from the ETOPO dataset. ETOPO is a 1 arc-minute(0.016 degree) global relief model of the Earths surface that integrates land topography and ocean bathymetry. Since it is modelled date there is a certain level of uncertainty associated with it. In this exercise, you will look at the differences between the elevations from the tower data, which is directly measured at the site, and the values you will extract from this modelled ETOPO data.

Note: think about which packages you need to load to complete each of the tasks.

  1. Load the dataset_ex3.csv file containing the elevations of the towers.

  1. Extract the elevations from the raster at the tower sites.
# enter your solution here
## generate the sp locations of towers
sp_sites <- SpatialPoints(dplyr::select(ele_towers, longitude, latitude))
## extract from the raster and join into original tower data
ele_towers_joined <- extract(raster_ETOPO, sp_sites, sp = TRUE) %>% 
  as_tibble() %>% 
  right_join(ele_towers, by = c("longitude", "latitude")) %>% 
  dplyr::rename(ele_ETOPO = ETOPO)
## new joined data
ele_towers_joined %>% head()

  1. Calculate the difference between the elevations of the towers and the one extracted from the ETOPO.
# enter your solution here
library(Metrics)
## use the MSE to measure the difference
cat("The MSE of two elevations is", mse(ele_towers_joined$ele_ETOPO, ele_towers_joined$elevation))
## The MSE of two elevations is 3262.667
  1. Plot the difference in elevation calculated for each site on a map of Europe. Hint: there are several ways to do this, one could be to using ifelse().
# enter your solution here
ele_towers_joined<-ele_towers_joined %>%
  mutate(ele_diff = elevation - ele_ETOPO)

## plot the difference so that if ele_diff > 0, then the symbol is upper red, or down blue.
cols_ele_diff <- ifelse(ele_towers_joined$ele_diff > 0,"red","blue")
pch_ele_diff <- ifelse(ele_towers_joined$ele_diff > 0, 24 , 25)

ggplot() +
  geom_polygon(data = europe_shape, aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group), fill=NA, colour = "black") +
  geom_point(data = ele_towers_joined, aes(x = longitude, y = latitude),color=cols_ele_diff, pch = pch_ele_diff, size=2) +
  labs(x = "Longitude", y = "Latitude") +
  theme_classic()+ 
  coord_quickmap()

Part 2: Temperature and Elevation Correlations

In this second part, we want to find out which of the elevations we gathered in the first part (ETOPO and towers) correlates better with the temperatures measured at the towers.

  1. Correlate the ETOPO elevations at the towers sites with the temperatures measured at the towers.
# enter your solution here
## do the pearson correlation test
cor.test(ele_towers_joined$ele_ETOPO, ele_towers_joined$temperature)
## 
##  Pearson's product-moment correlation
## 
## data:  ele_towers_joined$ele_ETOPO and ele_towers_joined$temperature
## t = -2.9946, df = 28, p-value = 0.005693
## alternative hypothesis: true correlation is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  -0.7242793 -0.1607900
## sample estimates:
##        cor 
## -0.4925282
## do the linear regression
reg1 <- lm(temperature ~ ele_ETOPO, data = ele_towers_joined)
summary(reg1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = temperature ~ ele_ETOPO, data = ele_towers_joined)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -11.5371  -3.2284   0.7566   2.9479   7.1683 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)   
## (Intercept)  1.725103   1.082327   1.594  0.12219   
## ele_ETOPO   -0.004330   0.001446  -2.995  0.00569 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 4.35 on 28 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.2426, Adjusted R-squared:  0.2155 
## F-statistic: 8.968 on 1 and 28 DF,  p-value: 0.005693
## plot the relationship
ele_towers_joined %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = ele_ETOPO, y = temperature)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method='lm', color="red", size=0.5, se=FALSE) +
  xlab("ETOPO elevation [m]") +
  ylab("Temperature [degree celcius]") +
  theme_classic()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

  1. Correlate the elevations measured at the tower sites with the temperatures measured at the towers.

  1. What is the mean squared errors of the two models above. Which of the two correlates better?
# enter your solution here
mse1 <- mean(reg1$residuals^2)
mse2 <- mean(reg2$residuals^2)
cat("MSE of the first model is",mse1,'and','MSE of the second model is',mse2)
## MSE of the first model is 17.65813 and MSE of the second model is 17.65501
  1. The lapse rate is known as the rate of decrease of an atmospheric variable, in our case temperature, with increased elevation (also altitude). This lapse (gradual fall) in temperature with increasing altitude at a given time and place, is the slope of your models above. Find and compare the lapse rate of the two models. Hint: if you are stuck take a closer look at your model with summary().
# enter your solution here
lapse_rate1 <- reg1$coefficients[2]
lapse_rate2 <- reg2$coefficients[2]
cat("Lapse rate of the first model is",lapse_rate1*100,'K/100m','and','lapse rate of the second model is',lapse_rate2*100,'K/100m.')
## Lapse rate of the first model is -0.4330472 K/100m and lapse rate of the second model is -0.4536285 K/100m.
